				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \text {PLQY} = \frac{k_{r}}{k_r + k_{ic} + k_{ISC}} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}

The VIBES software package29 was used to generate the Franck–Condon and Herzberg–Teller spectral densities, as well as calculate ISC rates, using 216\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$2^{16}$$\end{document} integration points with a 300 fs time integral for integration, and a 100 cm-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{-1}$$\end{document} width for the Gaussian damping of the calculated correlation function. A temperature of 300 K was assumed for all calculations. For IC rates, the Knapsack software package30 was used to compute IC rate constants. Employed parameters include using a Franck–Condon weighted density, and a contributions threshold of 15. Derivative components were calculated using a central difference method.

Using Vibes, the first order spectra can be calculated either dependant or independent of the transition dipole matrix elements. Both resulting spectra differ in spectral intensity, with this difference being related directly to the square of the transition dipole moment. From the normalisation factors of both dipole-dependant (ND\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N_D$$\end{document}) and dipole-independent (NI\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N_I$$\end{document}) spectra, this connection becomes more clear:4μ=NDNI\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \mu =\sqrt{\frac{N_D}{N_I}} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}From this link, we can approximate the second order corrected transition dipole moment. Vibes does not currently decouple the second order corrected transition dipole moment from the dipole-dependant spectra; as such we do not have access to the normalisation factor. However, if we assume minimal difference between the Franck–Condon and Herzberg–Teller corrected spectra, such that the second order contribution is not dominant, we can approximate an effective transition dipole moment which we can use to compute the rate constant.5kr,γ,FC+HT=4μγ23ħc3NI2∫Sd,FC+HT(ω)ω3dω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} k_{r,\gamma ,FC+HT} = \dfrac{4\mu _\gamma ^2}{3\hbar c^3 N^2_I}\int S_{d,FC+HT}(\omega )\omega ^3d\omega \end{aligned}$$\end{document}This approximation can be expected to work in any case where dominant contributions to the transition dipole moment come from Franck–Condon terms. In other words, where the change to the effective transition dipole is much smaller than or comparable in size/magnitude to the transition dipole at the Franck–Condon point:6AFC≈AFC+HT⇒μγ≈μ0,γ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} A_{FC} \approx A_{FC+HT} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \mu _\gamma \approx \mu _{0,\gamma } \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Naphthalene is known to depend on Herzberg–Teller components to fluoresce31–37 and as such, provides a perfect case study to examine the validity of this approximation. If the condition shown in Eq. (6) is not met, we can expect the spectrum to be un-normalised, therefore resulting in an overestimated fluorescence rate constant.

